Comment: Sean C. : You raise a consideration which deserves discussion, but has little merit for the following reasons:
1) The first two sentences in the Theroux quote are descriptive of the enviable Vietnamese characteristics. They are independent of the war with the USA.
2) The historical record is clear. Before the European arrival in Canada, aboriginal tribes were frequently at war with each other, and in some cases, perpetually at war. There were winners and losers.  The losers, when not annihilated or absorbed, went on with their lives as self-sufficient entities;
3) The Vietnamese who fled from what was then South Vietnam after the communist take-over in 1975 and came to Canada to build new lives (successfully as it turned out) did so without "blaming", "complaining " and "looking for pity";
4) The millions of Vietnamese who did not flee,  but were victims of communist oppression starting in 1975 are not consumed today with "blaming", "complaining", nor are they "looking for pity".

